  <section id="tips">
    <h2>In-Depth Resume Formatting and Writing Guidance</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">
      Strong resumes are not just about listing experiences; they are about presenting those experiences clearly and in a way that is easy for both people and systems to understand.
    </p>
    <div class="prose-flow">
      <h3>Readability Comes First</h3>
      <p>
        Start with a layout that is clean and predictable. Use consistent spacing, clear section headings, and readable fonts so a recruiter can scan the page in seconds. A resume should feel organized at a glance, with your most relevant qualifications appearing early. When formatting is inconsistent, even strong experience can look less polished than it really is.
      </p>
      <p>
        Keep visual clutter low by avoiding too many text styles, decorative icons, or dense blocks of content. If your resume looks crowded, separate ideas with whitespace and shorten long bullet points. A balanced layout improves readability and helps your key accomplishments stand out.
      </p>
      <h3>Write Bullet Points with Purpose</h3>
      <p>
        Every bullet point should communicate action and impact. Instead of describing duties only, show what you contributed and what improved because of your work. Good bullets often follow a simple pattern: action verb, task, and result. This approach helps your experience sound confident and specific rather than generic.
      </p>
      <p>
        Measurable detail is especially important. Numbers such as customer volume, time saved, sales growth, project size, or completion speed give context to your work. Even when exact metrics are not available, adding scale and scope makes your experience more believable and easier to evaluate.
      </p>
      <h3>Match the Role Without Losing Your Voice</h3>
      <p>
        Tailoring your resume means aligning wording with the job description while staying honest about your background. If a posting emphasizes collaboration, data entry, scheduling, or customer support, those terms should appear naturally in your resume when they truly reflect your experience. This helps with ATS visibility and makes your resume feel relevant to the role.
      </p>
      <p>
        Finally, proofread with intention. Review for grammar, tense consistency, and repeated phrases. AI tools can help identify rough spots, but your final pass matters most because it ensures the resume still sounds like you and accurately represents your work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="ai-hiring">
    <h2>AI in Resume Screening and Hiring</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">
      Once your resume is submitted, it is often reviewed by both software and people. Understanding how AI fits into that process helps you write more strategically.
    </p>
    <div class="prose-flow">
      <h3>How AI Helps Applicants and Recruiters</h3>
      <p>
        AI can support resume structure, wording, and clarity by identifying weak phrasing, repeated language, and missing keywords connected to a target role. For applicants, this can save time and reduce guesswork. Instead of editing from scratch every time, you can use AI feedback to quickly tighten bullet points and align your resume with specific responsibilities in a posting.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the hiring side, ATS and AI-assisted tools help teams organize large applicant pools, sort by qualifications, and create faster shortlists. This can improve consistency and reduce delays, especially when companies receive hundreds of applications. Used well, these systems make early-stage review more manageable and allow recruiters to focus their attention where it matters most.
      </p>
      <h3>Benefits of AI Support</h3>
      <p>
        One of the biggest advantages is efficiency. AI tools can generate revision ideas quickly, highlight gaps, and suggest phrasing that better matches role expectations. They can also help users tailor multiple versions of a resume for different industries by adjusting keywords and emphasis without rewriting every section from the beginning.
      </p>
      <p>
        AI can also improve organization by turning scattered notes into structured content. For students and early-career applicants, this is especially useful when translating class projects, part-time work, and volunteer roles into stronger professional statements.
      </p>
      <h3>Downsides and Risks to Watch</h3>
      <p>
        AI is not neutral by default. If hiring systems are trained on biased historical patterns, they may unintentionally reinforce unfair outcomes. Overreliance on keyword matching can also miss capable candidates whose resumes use different wording but show equivalent skills.
      </p>
      <p>
        Privacy is another concern. Resumes contain personal information, so users should be selective about where they upload documents and avoid sharing unnecessary details. There is also the risk of generic writing: when AI suggestions are copied without editing, resumes can sound repetitive and less authentic. Human review remains essential to ensure your resume is accurate, specific, and true to your real experience.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="samples">
